#, python-brace-format
msgid "**Analysis window:** {start} to {end}."
msgstr "**Analysis window:** {start} to {end}."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "**Bottom line:** the highest exposure-normalized near-miss rate is on **{name}** — about {rate} reports per {per} {unit} (95% CI {lo}–{hi}, n={n}){sig}. Because it is normalized by exposure, this is a rate, not just a busy street; still, it rests on {n} reports, so read it with the interval and the reporting-bias caveats below."
msgstr "**Bottom line:** the highest exposure-normalized near-miss rate is on **{name}** — about {rate} reports per {per} {unit} (95% CI {lo}–{hi}, n={n}){sig}. Because it is normalized by exposure, this is a rate, not just a busy street; still, it rests on {n} reports, so read it with the interval and the reporting-bias caveats below."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "**Exposure coverage:** {pct}% of segments have an exposure denominator. Segments without one are listed as *exposure unknown*, not ranked."
msgstr "**Exposure coverage:** {pct}% of segments have an exposure denominator. Segments without one are listed as *exposure unknown*, not ranked."

msgid "**MAUP transparency note:** how you draw the boundary can itself shift a rate (the Modifiable Areal Unit Problem). Corridor counts and exposure are sums of the same already-published, already-significant blocks above — no block is surfaced here that was withheld or non-significant on its own. Read the corridor rate as a complement to the block rates, not a replacement for them."
msgstr "**MAUP transparency note:** how you draw the boundary can itself shift a rate (the Modifiable Areal Unit Problem). Corridor counts and exposure are sums of the same already-published, already-significant blocks above — no block is surfaced here that was withheld or non-significant on its own. Read the corridor rate as a complement to the block rates, not a replacement for them."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "**Null calibration (we attacked our own dataset):** on {n} seeded label-shuffles of this city's own reports, with exposure and geometry held fixed, the hotspot method's empirical false-positive rate was {pct}% — see `{file}`."
msgstr "**Null calibration (we attacked our own dataset):** on {n} seeded label-shuffles of this city's own reports, with exposure and geometry held fixed, the hotspot method's empirical false-positive rate was {pct}% — see `{file}`."

msgid "**Over-represented vs exposure** (more reports than traffic alone predicts):"
msgstr "**Over-represented vs exposure** (more reports than traffic alone predicts):"

#, python-brace-format
msgid "**Report-intensity peak (KDE, not danger):** around {name}. This shows where reports concentrate, which is not the same as where risk is highest."
msgstr "**Report-intensity peak (KDE, not danger):** around {name}. This shows where reports concentrate, which is not the same as where risk is highest."

msgid "**Under-represented vs exposure** (quiet in the data, not necessarily safe):"
msgstr "**Under-represented vs exposure** (quiet in the data, not necessarily safe):"

#, python-brace-format
msgid "**Weather (association, not a risk rate):** {rws} of matched reports fell on wet days, while {bws} of days in the weather record were wet. Wet days usually carry far fewer riders, so this is an association to investigate, not a weather risk rate. Source: {src}."
msgstr "**Weather (association, not a risk rate):** {rws} of matched reports fell on wet days, while {bws} of days in the weather record were wet. Wet days usually carry far fewer riders, so this is an association to investigate, not a weather risk rate. Source: {src}."

msgid "*Small sample: too few timed reports to read these peaks with confidence.*"
msgstr "*Small sample: too few timed reports to read these peaks with confidence.*"

msgid "*Time-of-day breakdown withheld: too few timed reports to share without risking contributor privacy (k-anonymity).*"
msgstr "*Time-of-day breakdown withheld: too few timed reports to share without risking contributor privacy (k-anonymity).*"

#, python-brace-format
msgid "*{n} segment with fewer than {floor} reports is withheld from this brief and the open dataset to protect contributor privacy (k-anonymity).*"
msgid_plural "*{n} segments with fewer than {floor} reports are withheld from this brief and the open dataset to protect contributor privacy (k-anonymity).*"
msgstr[0] "*{n} segment with fewer than {floor} reports is withheld from this brief and the open dataset to protect contributor privacy (k-anonymity).*"
msgstr[1] "*{n} segments with fewer than {floor} reports are withheld from this brief and the open dataset to protect contributor privacy (k-anonymity).*"

msgid ", and it is a statistically significant cluster"
msgstr ", and it is a statistically significant cluster"

msgid "- **95% CI (confidence interval)** — the plausible range for the true rate. A wide range means few reports and real uncertainty; treat those rankings gently."
msgstr "- **95% CI (confidence interval)** — the plausible range for the true rate. A wide range means few reports and real uncertainty; treat those rankings gently."

msgid "- **Hotspot (Getis-Ord Gi\\*)** — a segment marked ★ Significant is hot *beyond* what traffic and chance explain, after a multiple-comparison correction: a real cluster, not a fluke. Several streets can share a rate while only one is a significant cluster."
msgstr "- **Hotspot (Getis-Ord Gi\\*)** — a segment marked ★ Significant is hot *beyond* what traffic and chance explain, after a multiple-comparison correction: a real cluster, not a fluke. Several streets can share a rate while only one is a significant cluster."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "- **Overdispersion (clustered reporting).** The report counts are overdispersed (dispersion ≈ {phi}): by that pooled estimate the Poisson 95% intervals above could be up to {infl}× too narrow. Genuine between-segment differences inflate this estimate too, so {infl}× is an upper bound on the needed widening. {clause}"
msgstr "- **Overdispersion (clustered reporting).** The report counts are overdispersed (dispersion ≈ {phi}): by that pooled estimate the Poisson 95% intervals above could be up to {infl}× too narrow. Genuine between-segment differences inflate this estimate too, so {infl}× is an upper bound on the needed widening. {clause}"

#, python-brace-format
msgid "- **Overdispersion.** Report counts show no material overdispersion (dispersion ≈ {phi}); the Poisson intervals stand as computed."
msgstr "- **Overdispersion.** Report counts show no material overdispersion (dispersion ≈ {phi}); the Poisson intervals stand as computed."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "- **Rate** — reports per {per} {unit}. It adjusts for how many people travel a street, so a quiet street with a few reports can rank above a busy one with many."
msgstr "- **Rate** — reports per {per} {unit}. It adjusts for how many people travel a street, so a quiet street with a few reports can rank above a busy one with many."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "- **Re-segmentation (MAUP).** Redrawing the network into {coarse} coarser units (from {fine}) leaves **{name}** the highest-rate, still-significant cluster — the hotspot is not an artifact of where the block lines were drawn. Top-{k} rank overlap: {overlap}."
msgstr "- **Re-segmentation (MAUP).** Redrawing the network into {coarse} coarser units (from {fine}) leaves **{name}** the highest-rate, still-significant cluster — the hotspot is not an artifact of where the block lines were drawn. Top-{k} rank overlap: {overlap}."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "- **Re-segmentation (MAUP).** Redrawing the network into {coarse} coarser units (from {fine}), **{name}** stays the highest-rate unit but loses statistical significance at the coarser scale — read it as scale-sensitive, a lead to confirm rather than a settled cluster. Top-{k} rank overlap: {overlap}."
msgstr "- **Re-segmentation (MAUP).** Redrawing the network into {coarse} coarser units (from {fine}), **{name}** stays the highest-rate unit but loses statistical significance at the coarser scale — read it as scale-sensitive, a lead to confirm rather than a settled cluster. Top-{k} rank overlap: {overlap}."

#, python-brace-format
msgid "- **{name}** — Gi* z = {z}, rate {rate}/{per} (CI {lo}-{hi}, n={n})"
